column240: Many of my answers were "Important" or "Very Important". The trouble with Mechatronics/Robotics is that they are interdisciplinary, but a student shouldn't be expected to complete more credit hours than a traditional engineering degree. I think the core competency of a mechatronics/robotics engineer should be system design, including the selection of components and interfaces as well as the design of a control system. The remainder of their curriculum should be the core classes of mechanical, electrical, computer, and software engineering. Unfortunately, this doesn't leave much room for electives or specialization. There is also the risk of the student taking classes he or she will use very little.

Being effective in the robotics area requires understanding robots and integration.  You need to focus on robot applications:  Robot reach, payload, and robot controller communications with other devices within the robot work cell such as the cell's PLC, operator HMI, and fixturing.  Robots must also communicate with I/O on their grippers in a material handling application, weld controllers in a welding application, special hardware like paint controller in a painting application.
Cycle time is a huge driving factor, it is a make or break for the entire robot system.  Most automotive applications work on a 60 second cycle time.   To be successful in robotics you must learn to subdivide tasks to get each piece of a task accomplished within this cycle time. 
Economics is another huge driving factor, does it make sense to design a robot system a given way?   If you have 2 robotic work stations you can buy one robot and a servo track to move the robot back and forth from station to station.   But, the cost of the servo track will buy the second robot what is gained?   The servo track's translation time is LOST since it must be added to each stations cycle time.
Application equipment, what you can and can't do technically, jig / tool design, machine design, vision applications and pit-falls.

Understanding these topics are necessary to be effective in robot applications.
column240:
Each robot company has certain features which need to be understood, Functional Safety Unit in Yaskawa-Motoman, Dual Check Safety in Fanuc, Safe Move in ABB.  These safety systems within the robot controllers need to be understood including how to use them.
RIA robotic safety standards are another huge topic which must be understood including light curtains,  laser floor scanners, time-distance safety calculations, collaborative robots and what constitutes a 'collaborative' robot application.
